canonical:
  title: 祝聖䟽
  author: 釋宓菴
  language: lzh
  text: 毫光照物十方無地之孑遺玉色違倪四海有誰之寧處况如鈍衲久荷優恩常切祈宸寢之燕安豈意致天和之乖戾聞來震駭叵堪五內之分崩思可醫治莫若三歸之精進故此熏筵之急展盡吾微懇以克勤誠其有加應必不阻伏願主上陛下仗百靈之翊衛承衆聖之提撕病孽旋消不假驢䭾之藥節宣恒適永膺龜負之圖
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 祝聖䟽
  author: 釋宓菴
  language: lzh
  text: 毫光照物。十方無地之孑遺。玉色違倪。四海有誰之寧處。况如鈍衲。久荷優恩。常切祈宸寢之燕安。豈意致天和之乖戾。聞來震駭。叵堪五內之分崩。思可醫治。莫若三歸之精進。故此熏筵之急展。盡吾微懇以克勤。誠其有加。應必不阻。伏願主上陛下。仗百靈之翊衛。承衆聖之提撕。病孽旋消。不假驢䭾之藥。節宣恒適。永膺龜負之圖。
korean:
  title: 우
  author: 석복암
  language: kor
  text: 부처님 옥호의 광명은 만물을 고루 비추어서, 시방 세계에 조금도 빠뜨림이 없으십니다. 임금님께서 병환[違倪]이 있으니 온 국토가 누군들 편할 리가 있습니까. 하물며 이 우둔한 중은 우악한 은덕을 오랫동안 입은 몸이라, 항상 대궐이 편안하기를 빌었는데, 이렇게 천화(天和)가 맞지 않으시다니, 듣기에 너무 놀라서 오장(五臟)이 찢어지는 듯합니다. 삼보께 귀의하여 정진을 다하여야 속히 치료가 될 줄로 생각되기에, 이 법식의 자리를 급히 마련하고 저희들의 조그마한 정성을 다하여 정근(精勤)합니다. 이 간곡한 정성에 부처님의 감응이 틀림이 없으소서. 엎드려 원합니다. 주상 폐하께서 1백 신령의 보호함에 의지하고 여러 성현들의 이끌어 줌을 받아서, 병이 속히 나으시어 말이 실어오는 약이 쓸모없게 되고, 절후가 항상 적절하셔서 거북 등의 그림에 길이 맞아지이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1150_010_0200&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Blessing Prayer for the Ruler
  author: Seok Bok-am
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Buddha's radiant light illuminates all things,
    Leaving no corner of the ten directions untouched.
    Yet when the Sovereign falls ill,
    Who in this realm can know true peace?

    How much more so for this dull monk,
    Who has long basked in undeserved grace,
    Always praying for the palace to dwell in tranquility—
    Now that Heaven's harmony grows strained,
    My heart trembles as though my very organs splinter.

    Thus we turn to the Three Jewels with redoubled devotion,
    For healing comes through sincere practice.
    We urgently prepare this dharma ceremony,
    Offering what meager sincerity we possess,
    Dedicated to wholehearted striving.

    May our fervent prayer not go unanswered!

    I humbly beseech: May the Sovereign, our Lord,
    Lean upon the protection of a hundred celestial spirits,
    And receive the guidance of all the sages.
    May illness swiftly fade,
    Rendering the donkey's medicine needless,
    And may the seasons ever favor Your Majesty,
    That you may long embody the fortune of the tortoise's back.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'ten directions' (十方) refers to all of space in Buddhist cosmology—the four cardinal directions, four intermediate directions, and the realms above and below.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Three Jewels' (三歸) are the Buddha, the Dharma, and the Sangha—the fundamental objects of refuge in Buddhism.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'donkey's medicine' alludes to a classical tale where an imperial physician's supernatural remedies become unnecessary when virtue restores natural order.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'tortoise's back' (龜負) references the ancient symbol of imperial longevity and cosmic order, alluding to the hope that the ruler's reign will endure as long and as steadily as the cosmic support provided by the celestial tortoise.
